en, Ihringen, Breisach, Baden, Germany":"Ihringen, Ihringen, Amt Breisach, Baden","Ihringen, Ihringen, Breisach, Freiburg, Baden, Germany":"Ihringen, Ihringen, Amt Breisach, Baden","Mengen, Schallstadt, Freiburg, Baden, Deutschland":"Mengen, Schallstadt, Amt Freiburg, Baden"},"en":{"1728–1788":"1728–1788","1735–Female":"1735–Deceased","–Female":"Deceased","1758–1829":"1758–1829","1753–1821":"1753–1821","1760–1837":"1760–1837","–Male":"Deceased","1788":"1788","1821":"1821","22 May 1753":"22 May 1753","25 April 1760":"25 April 1760","1753":"1753","4 November 1758":"4 November 1758","1760":"1760","1829":"1829","1728":"1728","1837":"1837","1758":"1758","1735":"1735","Weinheim, Rhein-Neckar-Kreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany":"Weinheim, Rhein-Neckar-Kreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany","Ihringen, Ihringen, Breisach, Baden, Germany":"Ihringen, Ihringen, Amt Breisach, Baden","Ihringen, Ihringen, Breisach, Freiburg, Baden, Germany":"Ihringen, Ihringen, Amt Breisach, Baden","Mengen, Schallstadt, Freiburg, Baden, Deutschland":"Mengen, Schallstadt, Amt Freiburg, Baden","nameMeanings":[{"name":"Jacoby","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["German, French, Walloon, Luxembourgish, and Jewish: Latinized (humanistic) patronymic from the personal name   Jacob   or   Jakob  , from <i>Jacobi</i>, the genitive of its Latin form <i>Jacobus</i>. Compare   Jacobi  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Jacob","meanings":["Jewish, English, Welsh, German, Portuguese, French (mainly Alsace and Lorraine), Walloon, Breton, Dutch, Flemish, Swedish, Danish, and Norwegian: derivative, via Latin <i>Jacob(us)</i>, from the Hebrew personal name <i>Ya‘aqob</i> (<i>Yaakov</i>). In the Bible, this is the name of the crafty younger twin brother of Esau (Genesis 25:26), who took advantage of the latter's hunger and impetuousness to persuade him to part with his birthright ‘for a mess of potage’. The name is traditionally interpreted as coming from Hebrew <i>akev</i> ‘heel’: Jacob is said to have been born holding on to Esau's heel. In English usage the name <i>Jacob</i> is regarded as distinct from the name   James  , but they are of identical origin. In North America, the English form of the surname has absorbed cognates from other languages, for example Assyrian/Chaldean or Arabic   Yaqub  ,   Yakub  ,   Yacoub  , or   Yacob  , Slovenian   Jakob   and <b>Jakop</b>, Czech and Slovak   Jakub  , and also their patronymics and other derivatives (see examples at   Jacobs   and   Jacobson  ). The name <i>Jacob</i> is also found among Christians in southern India (compare   Chacko  ), but since South Indians traditionally do not have hereditary surnames, the southern Indian name was in most cases registered as such only after immigration of its bearers to the US."]}]},{"name":"Johann","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Vernacular form of   Johannes ."],"variants":[{"name":"John","meanings":["As a boy's name this represents a revival of Middle English <i>Jan</i>, a by‐form of   John  , or an adoption of the common European form with this spelling. As a girl's name it is a short form of names such as   Janet   and   Janice ."]}]},{"name":"Francis","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["equivalent of Italian Francesco , originally a vocabulary word meaning ‘French’ or ‘Frenchman’ (Late Latin <i>Franciscus</i>;  compare  Frank  ). This was a nickname given to  St Francis  of Assisi (  1181–1226 ) because of his wealthy father's business connections with France. His baptismal name was  Giovanni . He had a pleasant, ordinary life as a child and young man, but after two serious illnesses, a period of military service, and a year as a prisoner of war in Perugia, he turned from the world and devoted himself to caring for the poor and sick. He was joined by groups of disciples, calling themselves ‘minor friars’ (<i>friari minores</i>). The main features of the Franciscan rule are humility, poverty, and love for all living creatures. The given name occurs occasionally in England as early as  1300 , and more frequently from the early 16th century, when there was a surge of admiration for, and imitation of, Italian Renaissance culture."],"variants":[]},{"name":"Lucas","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["In part a learned form of   Luke  , in part a transferred use of the surname derived from it in the Middle Ages. The Latin form <i>Lucas</i> was often used in the Middle Ages in written documents in place of the spoken vernacular form <i>Luke</i>, hence the common surname. It is also the spelling preferred in the Authorized Version of the New Testament, which has had some influence on its selection as a given name. There has been a sharp rise in its popularity since the turn of the century. <i>Lucas</i> is now also used as an Anglicized form of various Eastern European equivalents (  see the cognates listed at  Luke  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Luke","meanings":["Middle English vernacular form of   Lucas  , Latin form of the post-classical Greek name <i>Loukas</i> ‘man from Lucania’. This owes its perennial popularity throughout Christian Europe to the fact that, from the 2nd century onwards, the third gospel in the New Testament has been ascribed to the Lucas or Luke mentioned at various places in Acts and in the Epistles. Little is known about him beyond the facts that he was a doctor, a Gentile, and a friend and convert of St Paul. The name was borne by the character  Luke Skywalker  in the film Star Wars (  1977 ), and rose sharply in popularity in the 1990s."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"Johann Francis Lucas Jacoby was born in 1728 as the son of Johann Jacob. He married Anna Maria Graff in 1758, in Mengen, Schallstadt, Amt Freiburg, Baden. They were the parents of at least 1 son and 2 daughters. He died in 1788, at the age of 60."},"et":{"1728–1788":"1728–1788","1735–Female":"1735–Surnud","–Female":"Surnud","1758–1829":"1758–1829","1753–1821":"1753–1821","1760–1837":"1760–1837","–Male":"Surnud","1788":"1788","1821":"1821","22 May 1753":"22. mai 1753","25 April 1760":"25. aprill 1760","1753":"1753","4 November 1758":"4. november 1758","1760":"1760","1829":"1829","1728":"1728","1837":"1837","1758":"1758","1735":"1735","Weinheim, Rhein-Neckar-Kreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany":"Weinheim, Rhein-Neckar-Kreis, Baden-Württemberg, Saksamaa","Ihringen, Ihringen, Breisach, Baden, Germany":"Ihringen, Ihringen, Amt Breisach, Baden","Ihringen, Ihringen, Breisach, Freiburg, Baden, Germany":"Ihringen, Ihringen, Amt Breisach, Baden","Mengen, Schallstadt, Freiburg, Baden, Deutschland":"Mengen, Schallstadt, Amt Freiburg, Baden"},"fi":{"1728–1788":"1728–1788","1735–Female":"1735–Kuollut","–Female":"Kuollut","1758–1829":"1758–1829","1753–1821":"1753–1821","1760–1837":"1760–1837","–Male":"Kuollut","1788":"1788","1821":"1821","22 May 1753":"22. toukokuuta 1753","25 April 1760":"25. huhtikuuta 1760","1753":"1753","4 November 1758":"4. marraskuuta 1758","1760":"1760","1829":"1829","1728":"1728","1837":"1837","1758":"1758","1735":"1735","Weinheim, Rhein-Neckar-Kreis, Baden-Württemberg, Germany":"Weinheim, Rhein-Neckar-Kreis, Baden-Württemberg, Saksa","Ihringen, Ihringen, Breisach, Baden, Germany":"Ihringen, Ihringen, Amt Breisach, Baden","Ihringen, Ihringen, Breisach, Freiburg, Baden, Germany":"Ihringen, Ihringen, Amt Breisach, Baden","Mengen, Schallstadt, Freiburg, Baden, Deutschland":"Mengen, Schallstadt, Amt Freiburg, Baden"},"fr":{"1728–1788":"1728–1788","1735–Female":"1735–Décédée","–Female":"Décédée","1758–1829":"1758–1829","1753–1821":"1753–1821","1760–1837":"1760–1837","–Male":"Décédé","1788":"1788","1821":"1821","22 May 1753":"22 mai 1753","25 April 1760":"25 avril 1760","1753":"1753","4 November 1758":"4 novembre 1758","176